{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651263"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:21:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:21:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18439"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18439"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11157"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74716"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11157"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18439"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60199"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7716"},{"type":"tags","id":"7734"},{"type":"tags","id":"7760"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25866"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25871"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74716"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher wants to compare mean reaction times between two independent groups of participants who received different cognitive enhancement supplements. The data appear normally distributed with similar variances between groups.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statistical tests is most appropriate for this analysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mann-Whitney U test","Paired samples t-test","Chi-square test","Independent samples t-test","One-way analysis of variance"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eindependent samples t-test\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate test for comparing means between two unrelated groups when the data are normally distributed and have equal variances. This test determines whether the difference between group means is statistically significant by calculating a t-statistic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe independent samples t-test is appropriate here because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are two independent groups being compared\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe outcome (reaction time) is continuous\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe data are normally distributed\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe variances are similar between groups.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChi-square test\u003C/strong\u003E - Used for categorical data to test associations between variables, not for comparing means of continuous data\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPaired samples t-test\u003C/strong\u003E - Used when measurements are taken from the same subjects before and after an intervention, not for independent groups\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOne-way analysis of variance\u003C/strong\u003E - Used to compare means across three or more groups, not necessary for only two groups\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMann-Whitney U test\u003C/strong\u003E - A non-parametric alternative used when data are not normally distributed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The independent samples t-test compares means between two unrelated groups to determine if differences are statistically significant.","The t-test assumes data are normally distributed and have equal variances between groups."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60199"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18439"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60199"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T16:03:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T16:11:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11157"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74716"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"m